.TH VOIX 1 "March 2026" "Voix 2.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
voix \- privilege escalation tool replacing sudo/doas
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B voix
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Voix is a privilege escalation tool designed to replace sudo, doas, and sudo-rs.
It uses PAM for authentication and provides a secure, modern approach to privilege management.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-version
Show version information and exit.
.TP
.B \-u \fIUSER\fR, \-\-user \fIUSER\fR
Execute command as specified user (default: root).
.TP
.B \-g \fIGROUP\fR, \-\-group \fIGROUP\fR
Execute command as specified group.
.TP
.B \-S, \-\-shell
Start a shell as the target user.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Voix configuration is typically located in \fI/etc/voix.conf\fR.
The configuration file uses a simple syntax for defining access rules.
.SH AUTHENTICATION
Voix uses PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules) for authentication.
The PAM configuration is typically located in \fI/etc/pam.d/voix\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
Execute a command as root:
.IP
voix whoami
.PP
Execute a command as a specific user:
.IP
voix -u username whoami
.PP
Start a shell as root:
.IP
voix -S
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/voix.conf
Main configuration file for access rules.
.TP
.B /etc/pam.d/voix
PAM configuration for authentication.
.TP
.B /var/log/voix.log
Log file for voix commands (if configured).
.SH SECURITY
Voix should be owned by root and have the setuid bit set for proper functionality.
.SH AUTHOR
Veridian-Zenith Team
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sudo (8),
.BR doas (1),
.BR pam (8)
